            <pre class="text-xs bg-card rounded-lg p-3 overflow-x-auto text-emerald-400 leading-relaxed">// ── Sliding Window ──────────────────────────────────────
int left = 0, maxLen = 0;
Map&lt;Character, Integer&gt; freq = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
for (int right = 0; right &lt; s.length(); right++) &#123;
    freq.merge(s.charAt(right), 1, Integer::sum);
    while (freq.size() &gt; k) &#123;
        freq.merge(s.charAt(left), -1, Integer::sum);
        if (freq.get(s.charAt(left)) == 0) freq.remove(s.charAt(left));
        left++;
    &#125;
    maxLen = Math.max(maxLen, right - left + 1);
&#125;

// ── Binary Search ────────────────────────────────────────
int lo = 0, hi = arr.length - 1;
while (lo &lt;= hi) &#123;
    int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2; // avoids overflow
    if (arr[mid] == target) return mid;
    else if (arr[mid] &lt; target) lo = mid + 1;
    else hi = mid - 1;
&#125;

// ── Top-K with Min-Heap ──────────────────────────────────
PriorityQueue&lt;Integer&gt; minHeap = new PriorityQueue&lt;&gt;(k);
for (int num : nums) &#123;
    minHeap.offer(num);
    if (minHeap.size() &gt; k) minHeap.poll();
&#125;
// minHeap now contains top K largest elements

// ── BFS (shortest path) ──────────────────────────────────
Queue&lt;TreeNode&gt; q = new LinkedList&lt;&gt;();
q.offer(root);
while (!q.isEmpty()) &#123;
    int size = q.size(); // current level
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; size; i++) &#123;
        TreeNode node = q.poll();
        if (node.left != null) q.offer(node.left);
        if (node.right != null) q.offer(node.right);
    &#125;
&#125;</pre>
          </div>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

    <!-- 60-Second Cheat Sheet -->
    <section id="sec-cheatsheet" class="mb-8">
      <details class="group rounded-xl border border-border/30 bg-card/50 overflow-hidden">
        <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer select-none font-semibold text-foreground hover:bg-card/80 transition-colors">
          <span class="flex items-center gap-2"><span>⚡</span> 60-Second Cheat Sheet — 10 Core Principles</span>
          <span class="text-muted-foreground text-sm group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform">▼</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="p-5 pt-3 border-t border-border/20">
          <ol class="space-y-2.5">
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">1. Measure first, optimize second</strong> — instrument P99 latency + error rate + saturation before changing anything. Never guess bottlenecks.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">2. Stateless services = horizontal scaling</strong> — session state → Redis, files → S3. If a service can't be killed any time, it's not stateless.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">3. Idempotency is non-negotiable</strong> — every mutating API needs an idempotency key. Retries, network blips, and duplicate webhooks are facts of life.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">4. Every external call needs a circuit breaker</strong> — one downstream failure should never take down your service. Resilience4j, always.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">5. Eventual consistency is acceptable; data loss is not</strong> — design write paths for durability first, relax read consistency where product allows.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">6. Design for failure, not success</strong> — network is unreliable, disks fail, services crash. Chaos engineering validates assumptions.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">7. Observability beats monitoring</strong> — metrics + structured logs + distributed traces (RED: Rate, Errors, Duration). Alert on symptoms, not causes.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">8. Schema evolution must be backward compatible</strong> — add columns, never rename/drop in one deployment. Blue-green + rolling deploys require this.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">9. Caching is a read optimization</strong> — write-through only if you understand the invalidation strategy. Cache invalidation is hard.</li>
            <li class="text-sm text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">10. The 8 Fallacies of Distributed Systems</strong> — network is NOT reliable, NOT zero latency, NOT infinite bandwidth, NOT secure. Topology DOES change.</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

