            <div class="flex-1"><p class="text-sm font-medium text-foreground">Amazon Cart Shows Old Data</p><p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-0.5">Cache Invalidation · Eventual Consistency · Write-Through</p></div>
            <span class="shrink-0 text-muted-foreground text-xs">▼</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 border-t border-border/20 space-y-3">
            <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground"><strong class="text-foreground">Root Cause:</strong> Cart update writes to DB but cache still holds old version. Next read hits cache → stale data. Classic cache invalidation problem.</p>
            <div class="mermaid text-xs">
flowchart LR
  subgraph WRITE [Write — Cache-Aside]
    W([Update Cart]) --> DB[(DB)]
    DB -->|invalidate| R[("Redis\nDEL cart:userId")]
  end
  subgraph READ [Read — Cache-Aside]
    U([User]) --> C&#123;Cache hit?&#125;
    C -->|yes| D([Return cached])
    C -->|no| DB2[(DB)]
    DB2 -->|populate| R2[(Redis SET)]
    R2 --> D2([Return fresh])
  end
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-blue-400 bg-blue-500/5 border border-blue-500/20 rounded-lg px-3 py-2"><strong>Key insight:</strong> Delete the cache key on write (cache-aside), don't update it. Updating risks a race condition between the DB write and the cache write. DEL is atomic and safe. Cart can tolerate a single read-through on the next request.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

